		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Casuistry</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p><b>Casuistry</b> (pronounced <span title="Pronunciation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:IPA_for_English" title="Wikipedia:IPA for English">/ˈkæʒuːɨstri/</a></span>) is an <a href="/wiki/Applied_ethics" title="Applied ethics">applied ethics</a> term referring to <a href="/wiki/Case-based_reasoning" title="Case-based reasoning">case-based reasoning</a>. Casuistry is used in <a href="/wiki/Juridical" title="Juridical" class="mw-redirect">juridical</a> and ethical discussions of <a href="/wiki/Law" title="Law">law</a> and <a href="/wiki/Ethics" title="Ethics">ethics</a>, and often is a critique of <a href="/wiki/Principle" title="Principle">principle</a> or <a href="/wiki/Rule_base" title="Rule base" class="mw-redirect">rule-based</a> reasoning.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Critics use the term pejoratively for the use of clever but unsound reasoning, especially in relation to moral questions (see <a href="/wiki/Sophistry" title="Sophistry" class="mw-redirect">sophistry</a>). Casuistry is reasoning used to resolve moral problems by applying theoretical rules to particular instances.</p>
<table id="toc" class="toc" summary="Contents">
<tr>
<td>
